<br>
Radioactive plutonium powers NASA's grandest close-up probe of Saturn.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://detnews.com/pix/2000/02/11/a11nuke1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
The 3,420-pound Cassini Orbiter's objective is a close-up study of Saturn. Images of the planet and its rings will be a 1,000 fold better than those from the Voyager. <br>
<br>
<br>
By Lawrence Spohn / Scripps Howard News Service.<br>
<br>
<br>
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- While environmental activists recently blasted New Mexico labs for &quot;nuclearizing&quot; space, rocket scientist Earl H. Maize just said thanks. <br>
    Maize, who is spacecraft operations manager for the Cassini Mission at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, said he doesn't mind those who oppose nuclear power in space -- so long as the American people understand that without it NASA's grandest planetary explorer would be impossible. <br>
    NASA's 12,000-pound Cassini spacecraft is hurtling toward Saturn, and Maize said that mission and many others needed electric generators powered by the heat of radioactive plutonium to complete their scientific missions. <br>
    With three such nuclear generators on board, the $2 billion Cassini interplanetary cruiser is by far the biggest and most ambitious robotic explorer ever launched by NASA. <br>
    Among the returns to Earth, images of Saturn and its rings that will be a &quot;1,000 fold&quot; better than the best in existence today (from the Voyager), Maize said. <br>
    Maize said he believes the courts and the American people understand and accept the minor risks associated with Cassini and other nuclear-powered spacecraft and believe the benefits hugely outweigh any danger. <br>
    Maize remarked to rousing cheers that following Cassini's controversial fly-by of Earth last year in the final twist of a complicated trajectory to get the heavy craft to Saturn, he &quot;didn't expect to see any more protesters.&quot; <br>
    &quot;But it looks like they are alive and well,&quot; he said. <br>
    Before Cassini's Earth fly-around last August, opponents had warned the spacecraft could crash into Earth and contaminate it with vaporized plutonium that could cause cancer in millions of people. <br>
    NASA and the Department of Energy, whose labs produced the Cassini plutonium generators, insisted there was little if any danger. <br>
    About 25 protesters, representing the Global Network Against Weapons and Nuclear Power in Space paraded the other day outside the space conference, and accused New Mexico labs of helping plant &quot;the bad seed&quot; in space. <br>
    &quot;They are establishing a foothold with deep-space explorations and talk of a manned mission to Mars,&quot; said Bruce Gagnon, the network's coordinator. <br>
    He said NASA's programs and the conference, organized annually by the University of New Mexico's Institute for Space Nuclear Power Studies, are a smoke screen to &quot;disguise&quot; United States militarization of space. <br>
    Maize expressed his gratitude to the Department of Energy labs here that have helped Jet Propulsion Laboratory fuel its interplanetary discoveries. <br>
    Maize described the plutonium fuel prepared and specially packaged for Cassini at Los Alamos National Laboratory as &quot;mission-enabling because there would not be a mission without that power supply.&quot; <br>
    Similar generators were developed at Los Alamos for the Galileo mission to study Jupiter, and that spacecraft also benefited from special radiation-hardened computer chips produced at Sandia National Laboratories in Albuquerque. <br>
    The special chips were designed to survive intense radiation fields surrounding Jupiter and its moons. <br>
    While Gagnon said his group is organizing an international movement opposing nuclear devices in space, Maize said Cassini is evidence of the strong international support for using nuclear power to explore space. <br>
